ounds, leading to symptoms such as hives, itching, and difficulty breathing. Developing digestive issues is also a possible outcome, as the plant contains isothiocyanates, which can cause stomach upset, nausea, and diarrhea in some individuals. Skin irritation is another potential side effect, particularly if the plant's sap comes into contact with the skin, causing redness, itching, and inflammation. Furthermore, consuming Brassica campestris stirps napobrassica in excess can lead to gastrointestinal issues such as diarrhea and abdominal pain due to its high cruciferous content.", "category-action": "anti-inflammatory", "category_action": "anti-inflammatory", "family_slug": "brassicaceae", "family_name": "Brassicaceae", "what_description": "Brassica campestris stirps napobrassica is a plant variety that belongs to the family Brassicaceae, characterized by its annual habit, erect stem, and glabrous leaves with simple and alternate arrangement. The leaves are ovate to lanceolate in shape, with a glabrous or sparsely hairy surface and a dentate margin. This plant variety produces yellow flowers in racemes, which are 10-30 cm long and have 4-6 petals. The fruit is a siliqua, 5-10 cm long and 0.5-1.5 cm wide, dehiscent and containing 20-40 seeds. The plant is cultivated for its edible roots, which are used as a vegetable in various cuisines."}